In front of Parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was preparing a small stage and removing chairs in front of tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
"We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads held high, not through the back door," Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want us to enter as Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership would bring the much-needed investment Macedonia, whose unemployment rate is over 20 percent.
"I think the vast majority will be in favour, as more than 80% of citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive result would be a "confirmation of our future."
A poll published last Monday by the Institute for Policy Research said that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, which is less than the required turnout.
