"The sea belongs to us": a landlocked Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
Sailors guard a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings, navy blue flags are waving.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases show the motto: "The sea belongs to us by right,
Recovering it is a duty.”
Across Bolivia, a land without sea, they still vividly remember the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, as well as the desire to sail again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the highest in decades, as Bolivia expects a resolution from the International Court of Justice by October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the ruling of the International Court of Justice on big screens scattered across the country, in the hope that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has the obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is waging a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has much to say about Monday’s resolution.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to allocate Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the decision of the International Court of Justice comes just six months after the final arguments indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
Far from advancing Bolivia’s cause, the past four years may have hampered it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
In addition, he suggested that Morales’ belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold talks after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making was unusually swift.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and the possibility of “ending 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefit,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America, used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean,” he said.
“The resolution is an opportunity to see that we have to leave the past behind.”
