John Edward: Language skills are fundamental for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued into 2018 with another set of extraordinary test scores reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in schools.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, it reaches his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you can’t rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that are part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key competence that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK’s Committee on Employment and Skills revealed that, of the reasons employers gave for the difficulties they encountered in filling jobs, 17% were attributable to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities requiring languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of which career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically get ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and the only two-digit language spoken, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centers will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you can always choose between several languages taught by teaching staff specialized in this subject.
Independent schools in Scotland devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
At the moment, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges.
