North Korea says there's 'no chance' they will disarm unilaterally first if they don't have confidence
On Saturday, North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations that the continued sanctions deepened his distrust of the United States and that there was no chance his country would unilaterally give up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the international body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" over the past year, including stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we did not receive any similar response from the United States," he said.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence regarding our national security, and under those circumstances, there’s no chance we’ll disarm unilaterally first.”
Although Ri repeated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization without further ado, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump following the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work toward the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must renounce its nuclear weapons earlier.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, including by objecting to a declaration of ending the war," Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of the sanctions deepens our distrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader announced to the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, the leader of South Korea, in the last five months, adding: “If South Korea had been the party interested in denuclearization instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles toward U.S. soil after “evil president” Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim “rocket man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in advancing toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that it was necessary to continue to apply sanctions until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline set for this: “We can take two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its progress.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo informed the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without breach until we realize definitive and fully verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang’s ballistic and nuclear missile programs.
Pompeo chatted with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip didn’t go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea denounced his “requirements as those of a mobster.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had communicated to him that the “corresponding measures” he was seeking were the security assurances Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
Thanks to a new course being taught this year at Harvard University, all college students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing sexist culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found that students at the world’s number one university often have no idea about basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, believed to be the first of its kind in the U.S.
His motivation to start the course came after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked me why she just found out about this now, in her senior year.
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of dreaming, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleeping habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students barely slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a bedroom, where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers, and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on athletic performance, and the importance of establishing a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed of how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression, and cancer.
Then, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it’s not going to change students’ behavior instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco," Czeisler added.
He claimed that the culture of pride in "sleeping overnight" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure students are subjected to meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and good quality sleep should be students' "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, which is why they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the year before during his first year at Harvard.
He noted that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to extend it to the entire campus.
He hopes the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler’s recommendation is that students think about setting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble falling asleep.
