Syria ready for refugees to return, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is seeking help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has already lasted more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country’s conditions were improving.
“The situation on the ground is now more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists in an attempt to restore normalcy.
All conditions were already in place for the voluntary return of refugees who had to leave the country due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country and in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would appreciate help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that promoted the insurgency.
Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team has won the 2018 Ryder Cup by defeating the North American team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National, just outside Paris (France).
The United States now has six consecutive losses on European soil since the last time it won a Ryder Cup in Europe in 1993.
Europe regained the crown when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn scored the 14.5 points needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had to fight for most of the tournament, threw his starting point into the water in the 16 par 3 hole, thus admitting his defeat to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari stood out in all of his rounds, becoming one of four players to have never scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament's current format began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth fell 5 and 4 to the player with the lowest classification of the European team, the Danish Thorbjorn Olesen.
The world's number one player, Dustin Johnson, fell 2-1 to England's Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
Spain's Sergio Garcia, a veteran who already has eight Ryder Cups, became the European with the most tournament wins of all time, with 25.5 points in his career.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I can’t help it.
