Now it is up to us to bow our heads.
They have overtaken us.”
Red tide update: Decreased concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
Over the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and its coast, low-to-high concentrations in Hillsborough County, high-to-bottom concentrations in Manatee County, high-to-bottom concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, medium-to-bottom concentrations in Charlotte County, low-to-bottom concentrations in Collier County, and high-to-bottom concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
